"# Chapter 9 — Modal Logic: Necessity, Possibility, and Kripke Worlds

Where we add two operators — *necessarily* and *possibly* — and
discover that the same trick supports reasoning about time, knowledge,
obligation, and program correctness.

Modal logic is what you get when you enrich propositional logic with
*modes* — operators that qualify truth. The two classic modes are
alethic:

- `□P` — *necessarily P*, P is true in every possibility.
- `◇P` — *possibly P*, P is true in some possibility.

These operators do not fit into truth-functional propositional logic
because their truth depends not just on P's truth but on *which
possibilities exist and how they relate*. That extra structure — the
possibility space — is what modal semantics captures.

The modern semantics was invented by Kripke in the late 1950s. Modal
logic became suddenly rigorous, testable, and useful. Today it
underlies epistemic reasoning (knowledge, belief), temporal reasoning
(before/after), deontic reasoning (obligation, permission), and formal
verification of concurrent systems (invariants, liveness).

We will build a small modal-logic engine in Scheme. The engine has two
parts: a *Kripke frame* (worlds and relations) and an *evaluator* that
tells you whether a modal formula is true at a given world.

> **the runtime says**
>
> *The move from propositional to modal logic is like the move from
> propositional to predicate: you gain a whole dimension of expressive
> power for the cost of some formal machinery. Where predicate logic
> lets you talk about many objects at once, modal logic lets you talk
> about many possibilities at once. Once you have both, most of the
> reasoning humans actually do is expressible.*

## Kripke frames

A *Kripke frame* is a pair (W, R) where:

- W is a non-empty set of *worlds*.
- R is a binary *accessibility relation* on W. `w R w'` means *from w
  you can see w'*.

A *Kripke model* adds an interpretation: a function V that assigns to
each atomic proposition the set of worlds in which it is true.

```scheme
(define example-frame
  '((:worlds (w1 w2 w3))
    (:accessible ((w1 w2) (w1 w3) (w2 w2) (w3 w3)))
    (:valuation
     ((P . (w1 w2))
      (Q . (w2 w3))))))
```

Three worlds; w1 can see w2 and w3; w2 can see itself; w3 can see
itself. P is true at w1 and w2; Q is true at w2 and w3.

## Semantics: truth at a world

The truth of a modal formula is *relative to a world*. Write
`M, w ⊨ φ` for *φ is true at world w in model M*.

    M, w ⊨ P             iff  w ∈ V(P)                          [atomic]
    M, w ⊨ ¬φ            iff  not (M, w ⊨ φ)
    M, w ⊨ (φ ∧ ψ)       iff  (M, w ⊨ φ) and (M, w ⊨ ψ)
    M, w ⊨ (φ ∨ ψ)       iff  (M, w ⊨ φ) or  (M, w ⊨ ψ)
    M, w ⊨ (φ → ψ)       iff  if (M, w ⊨ φ) then (M, w ⊨ ψ)
    M, w ⊨ (□φ)          iff  for all w' with w R w': (M, w' ⊨ φ)
    M, w ⊨ (◇φ)          iff  there exists w' with w R w' and (M, w' ⊨ φ)

The two new clauses are the interesting ones. `□φ` at w means every
world reachable from w satisfies φ. `◇φ` at w means some world
reachable from w satisfies φ.

```scheme
(define (accessible-worlds w frame)
  (map cadr
       (filter (lambda (edge) (eq? (car edge) w))
               (cdr (assq :accessible frame)))))

(define (holds-atomic p w frame)
  (let ((valuation (cdr (assq :valuation frame))))
    (member w (cdr (assq p valuation)))))

(define (eval-modal phi w frame)
  (cond
    ((symbol? phi)
     (holds-atomic phi w frame))
    ((eq? (car phi) 'not)
     (not (eval-modal (cadr phi) w frame)))
    ((eq? (car phi) 'and)
     (and (eval-modal (cadr phi)  w frame)
          (eval-modal (caddr phi) w frame)))
    ((eq? (car phi) 'or)
     (or  (eval-modal (cadr phi)  w frame)
          (eval-modal (caddr phi) w frame)))
    ((eq? (car phi) 'implies)
     (or (not (eval-modal (cadr phi) w frame))
         (eval-modal (caddr phi) w frame)))
    ((eq? (car phi) 'box)
     (every (lambda (w2) (eval-modal (cadr phi) w2 frame))
            (accessible-worlds w frame)))
    ((eq? (car phi) 'diamond)
     (any (lambda (w2) (eval-modal (cadr phi) w2 frame))
          (accessible-worlds w frame)))))
```

Ten lines of semantics. Run it.

```scheme
(eval-modal '(box P) 'w1 example-frame)
;; => #t iff P holds at every world w1 can see: w2 and w3.
;;    P holds at w2 (yes) and at w3 (no). So (box P) is #f at w1.

(eval-modal '(diamond P) 'w1 example-frame)
;; => #t (P holds at w2, and w1 can see w2).

(eval-modal '(box (or P Q)) 'w1 example-frame)
;; => #t (at w2, P holds; at w3, Q holds; so (P ∨ Q) holds at both).
```

That last is illustrative. `(□(P ∨ Q))` is true at w1 because every
world accessible from w1 satisfies at least one of P and Q. But `(□P ∨ □Q)`
is false at w1 — neither P nor Q holds at every accessible world. Modal
distribution over disjunction fails.

## Modal axioms and the systems K, T, S4, S5

Modal logic is not a single logic — it is a *family* of logics, each
determined by which axioms hold. The base system is called **K**, after
Kripke. K contains only:

- All propositional tautologies.
- `K axiom: □(P → Q) → (□P → □Q)`  (distribution of box over implication).
- `Necessitation rule: if ⊢ P then ⊢ □P`  (theorems are necessary).

That is the base. Depending on what you want to model, you strengthen K
with more axioms.

- **T = K + □P → P**. What is necessary is actual. Corresponds to
  reflexive frames (`w R w` for all w). *Alethic modal logic.*
- **S4 = T + □P → □□P**. Iterated necessity is necessity. Corresponds to
  reflexive + transitive frames. *Epistemic reasoning about a persistent
  knower.*
- **S5 = S4 + ◇P → □◇P**. If something is possible, that possibility
  itself is necessarily possible. Corresponds to reflexive + transitive
  + symmetric frames (i.e., equivalence relations). *Metaphysical
  necessity; logical omniscience.*

These correspondences are called *Sahlqvist correspondence theorems*
and they are one of the deepest results in modal logic: certain axioms
correspond exactly to certain frame properties.

```scheme
(define (reflexive? frame)
  (every (lambda (w)
           (member w (accessible-worlds w frame)))
         (cdr (assq :worlds frame))))

(define (transitive? frame)
  (let ((worlds (cdr (assq :worlds frame))))
    (every (lambda (w)
             (every (lambda (u)
                      (every (lambda (v)
                               (implies (and (member u (accessible-worlds w frame))
                                             (member v (accessible-worlds u frame)))
                                        (member v (accessible-worlds w frame))))
                             worlds))
                    worlds))
           worlds)))

(define (symmetric? frame)
  (let ((worlds (cdr (assq :worlds frame))))
    (every (lambda (w)
             (every (lambda (u)
                      (implies (member u (accessible-worlds w frame))
                               (member w (accessible-worlds u frame))))
                    worlds))
           worlds)))
```

If your frame is reflexive, T holds. If reflexive and transitive, S4
holds. If reflexive, transitive, and symmetric, S5 holds. Design your
frame; know your logic.

## Epistemic reading

The most fruitful modern application is *epistemic modal logic*, where
`□φ` reads *the agent knows φ*.

- T says: what you know is true. (You cannot know a falsehood.)
- S4 says: what you know, you know that you know. (Positive
  introspection.)
- S5 says: what you *do not* know, you know that you do not know.
  (Negative introspection.)

S5 is the logic of an idealized omniscient reasoner who has perfect
introspection. Real humans do not satisfy S5 — we do not always know
what we do not know. But S5 is a useful *model*, and much of computer
science's reasoning about *distributed knowledge* uses it (Fagin,
Halpern, Moses, Vardi — *Reasoning About Knowledge*, 1995).

With multiple agents (Alice, Bob), you have multiple modalities:
`K_alice φ`, `K_bob φ`, etc. Now you can express:

- `K_alice (K_bob P)` — Alice knows that Bob knows P.
- `K_alice (¬K_bob P)` — Alice knows that Bob does not know P.
- `¬K_alice (K_bob P)` — Alice does not know whether Bob knows P.

Adding a *common knowledge* modality `C_G` — φ is common knowledge
among group G — is famously subtle: `C_G φ` means everyone knows φ,
everyone knows that everyone knows φ, and so on ad infinitum. Cryptographic
protocols use exactly this notion of common knowledge to reason about
what an adversary can and cannot infer.

## Deontic reading

`□φ` reads *it is obligatory that φ*, and `◇φ` reads *it is permitted
that φ*. Deontic modal logic.

- `¬◇P ↔ □¬P`: what is not permitted is forbidden.
- `□P → ¬□¬P` (deontic D): if you must do P, you may not be required to
  do not-P. Rules out contradictory obligations.

Deontic logic captures the structure of *systems of rules* — legal
codes, contracts, policies. It is useful because it makes contradictions
in rule systems explicit: if a policy demands both P and ¬P, the deontic
formulas capture that inconsistency.

## Program correctness

`□P` can be read *P holds throughout the program's execution* and `◇P`
as *P eventually holds*. This is a very small taste of *temporal logic*,
which we treat in chapter 10.

More directly, modal logic underlies *Hoare logic*: `{P} c {Q}` means
*if P holds before c executes, Q holds after*. This can be recast
modally as `[c] (P → Q)`, where `[c]` is a modality parameterized by
the program c. This is *dynamic logic* (Pratt, 1976).

## Composition: multiple modalities

Real reasoning often needs several modalities at once.

- Time + knowledge: *Alice knows now that Bob will know tomorrow.*
- Space + obligation: *Everyone in this building must wear a mask.*
- Belief + counterfactual: *If Alice had known, she would have acted.*

Each modality is a separate operator with its own accessibility
relation, and formulas can nest them arbitrarily. The engine we built
above generalises: index the frame with a *set* of accessibility
relations, one per modality, and add cases to the evaluator.

## Canonical models and completeness

For each of K, T, S4, S5, there is a completeness theorem: the axioms
prove exactly the formulas that are semantically valid in the
corresponding class of frames. The classic proof technique is the
*canonical model construction*: build a model whose worlds are
maximally-consistent sets of formulas, define accessibility so that
w R w' iff every `□φ` in w has φ in w'. Show that a formula is true at
w iff it is in w. Instant completeness.

The full development is Blackburn-de Rijke-Venema, chapters 4-5. It is
a beautiful piece of proof theory.

## Bisimulation

Two modal models are *bisimilar* if there is a relation between their
worlds preserving atomic truths and matching accessibility both ways.
Bisimilar worlds satisfy the same modal formulas — bisimulation is the
appropriate notion of *sameness* for modal models.

This matters computationally. If two systems (say two concurrent
processes) are bisimilar, they satisfy the same modal temporal
properties — every safety and liveness property that holds of one holds
of the other. Bisimulation-based process algebras (CCS, CSP, pi-
calculus) use this equivalence as their notion of behavioral
equality.

```scheme
;; A sketch: two worlds w and w' are bisimilar (relative to a relation R)
;; iff they agree on all atomic propositions and for every world u
;; accessible from w, there is a world u' accessible from w' with (u,u') in R
;; (and vice versa).
```

## Kripke and constructive modal logic

Modal logic has a *constructive* variant: intuitionistic modal logic.
The correspondence extends — modal S4 corresponds to *staged
computation*, where `□P` is *a computation that produces P at a later
stage*. This is the Davies-Pfenning 1996 correspondence and it
underlies modern research on multi-stage languages, macro systems, and
metaprogramming.

The pattern: every modality gives rise to a computational effect. Boxed
values are *stage-portable* values. Diamond-values are *possible*
values in some non-deterministic sense. The type-theoretic reading of
modality is one of the currently most active corners of the
Curry-Howard programme.

## Variations to try

Extend the frame with multiple modalities — one for each of two agents,
say. Now the syntax includes `(K-alice φ)` and `(K-bob φ)`. Rewrite the
evaluator to handle both. Then encode a *common knowledge* modality as
the fixed point of *everyone-knows*: `C φ = φ ∧ E φ ∧ E(E φ) ∧ ...`.
The full common-knowledge modality does not terminate on infinite
models; on finite models the fixed-point iteration converges. Try it
on a two-agent puzzle.

Build a *model checker*: given a frame and a formula, report the set of
worlds where the formula is true. This is essentially the evaluator
run at every world, collected. It is the seed of what real model
checkers do for temporal logic (chapter 10).

## Try this

Set up a Kripke frame with three worlds, w1 = *rainy*, w2 = *sunny*,
w3 = *snowy*, and accessibility that models weather transitions (say,
rainy → sunny, sunny → rainy or snowy, snowy → snowy). Add an atomic
proposition *outdoor-activity-possible* true at sunny only. Ask
questions: at w1, is `◇ outdoor-activity-possible` true (yes)? At w3,
`□ outdoor-activity-possible` (definitely not)? Play with the frame;
add new worlds; adjust the relation. This is what modal logic feels
like once you internalise it — a semantic sandbox for reasoning about
possibilities.

## Closing

Modal logic adds two operators to propositional logic and gains a
whole dimension of expressive power. Frames-and-relations semantics
gives it precise meaning. The axiom systems K, T, S4, S5 correspond
exactly to frame properties. Applications span knowledge, obligation,
time, and program verification.

Chapter 10 zooms in on one of these applications: temporal logic, where
worlds are moments in time, accessibility is *time-after*, and we can
formally verify properties like *once the system enters this state, it
never leaves*. This is what model checkers do, and it has caught real
bugs in real critical systems.
"
